    <body>
        
        <div type="letter">
            <div type="text">
                <opener>
                    <placeName>Museum, Jermyn St</placeName>
                    <date>15<hi rend="superscript">th</hi>. Nov<hi rend="superscript">r</hi>. 1860.</date>
                    <salute>My dear M<hi rend="superscript">r</hi>. Darwin</salute>
                </opener>
                <div type="transcription">
                     
<p>It really gives me much pleasure to be able to render you any assistance in your interesting experiments and I hope you will never hesitate to let me know where or when I can be of use.<ref target="#foot.f1"/></p>
<p>On the other side you have the weights of the three objects.<ref target="#foot.f2"/> I first weighed them myself in our own balance, and then I asked my friend M<hi rend="superscript">r</hi>. Tookey,<ref target="#foot.f3"/> who is known for his carefulness and accuracy, to do the same in his own assay-balance, which he considers to be about as accurate as can be made.</p>
<p>I may say that in both these balances “the beam is kicked” by the <formula><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>1000</mn></mfrac></math></formula> of a grain or .001 and practically I do not think Chemists attempt anything more delicate.</p>
<p>The difference in the weights I think may be explained by hydroscopic moisture as they were weighed on different days.</p> 
<figure type="diagram"> 
<p>[diag]</p> </figure> 
<p>Believe me, Yours very sincerely | Trenham Reeks.</p> 
                </div>
            </div>

        </div>

        

        

        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1">Reeks was curator and librarian of the Museum of Practical Geology, London. He had previously helped CD with his research.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f2">Reeks refers to the verso of the letter, on which he gave the weights of the materials sent to him by CD.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f3"><ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_4775.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Charles Tookey</ref> was employed in the Metallurgical Laboratory of the Royal School of Mines.</note>
        </div>        
            
